<subSubSection id="94E43CFDFFAD9E2EFF20FB2DE450FAC1" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="DC416F76FFAD9E2EFF20FB2DE450FAC1" blockId="0.[151,1436,1243,1482]" pageId="0" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis id="EE8AB364FFAD9E2EFF20FB2DE162FB28" bold="true" box="[151,279,1243,1269]" pageId="0" pageNumber="67">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Similar to 
<taxonomicName id="1BFE14F5FFAD9E2EFE2CFB2DE251FB29" authorityName="Coues" authorityYear="1874" box="[411,548,1243,1268]" class="Aves" family="Emberizidae" genus="Amphispiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EE8AB364FFAD9E2EFE2CFB2DE251FB29" box="[411,548,1243,1268]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="67">Amphispiza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but wing shorter relative to the tarsus, and tail longer (
<bibRefCitation id="B86F1287FFAD9E2EFB1EFB2DE5FAFB28" author="Ridgway, R." box="[1193,1423,1243,1269]" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" refId="ref795" refString="Ridgway, R. (1901) The birds of North and Middle America. Bulletin of the United States National Museum, no. 50, pt. 1. Washington, D. C., 715 pp." type="book" year="1901">Ridgway 1901:262</bibRefCitation>
). Molecular analysis also reveals differences in mitochondrial DNA sequences.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="94E43CFDFFAD9E2EFF70FADEE508FA17" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="DC416F76FFAD9E2EFF70FADEE2FBFABF" blockId="0.[151,1436,1243,1482]" pageId="0" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis id="EE8AB364FFAD9E2EFF70FADEE13DFA9D" bold="true" box="[199,328,1320,1344]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" reason="1">Etymology.</emphasis>
The feminine name combines the Latin generic name for sagebrush (
<taxonomicName id="1BFE14F5FFAD9E2EFB88FADFE4D2FA9D" box="[1087,1191,1321,1344]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Artemisia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EE8AB364FFAD9E2EFB88FADFE4D2FA9D" box="[1087,1191,1321,1344]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="67">Artemisia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from the Greek word 
<taxonomicName id="1BFE14F5FFAD9E2EFF20FABDE09FFABF" box="[151,234,1355,1378]" class="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" family="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" genus="Artemis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Crustacea (awaiting allocation)" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="EE8AB364FFAD9E2EFF20FABDE09FFABF" box="[151,234,1355,1378]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="67">Artemis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) with the Greek word for finch (
<emphasis id="EE8AB364FFAD9E2EFDFFFABDE20AFABF" box="[584,639,1355,1378]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="67">spiza</emphasis>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DC416F76FFAD9E2EFF70FA9BE508FA17" blockId="0.[151,1436,1243,1482]" pageId="0" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis id="EE8AB364FFAD9E2EFF70FA9BE10EFA58" bold="true" box="[199,379,1389,1413]" pageId="0" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis id="EE8AB364FFAD9E2EFF70FA9BE11FFA58" box="[199,362,1389,1413]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" reason="1">Included taxa.</emphasis>
I
</emphasis>
n addition to the 
<typeStatus id="0345D1D4FFAD9E2EFD84FA98E214FA58" box="[563,609,1390,1413]" pageId="0" pageNumber="67">type</typeStatus>
species, this genus includes the species 
<taxonomicName id="1BFE14F5FFAD9E2EFBA5FA98E577FA58" authority="(Ridgway)" baseAuthorityName="Ridgway" box="[1042,1282,1390,1413]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Artemisia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="nevadensis">
<emphasis id="EE8AB364FFAD9E2EFBA5FA98E4F2FA58" box="[1042,1159,1390,1413]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="67">nevadensis</emphasis>
(Ridgway)
</taxonomicName>
, which 
<bibRefCitation id="B86F1287FFAD9E2EFAE0FA98E0ABFA7A" author="Rising, J. D." pageId="0" pageNumber="67" refId="ref836" refString="Rising, J. D. (1996) A guide to the identification and natural history of the sparrows of the United States and Canada. Academic Press, San Diego." type="book" year="1996">Rising (1996)</bibRefCitation>
recognized as distinct and 
<bibRefCitation id="B86F1287FFAD9E2EFDBAFA66E2A7FA7A" author="Cicero, C." box="[525,722,1424,1447]" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" refId="ref622" refString="Cicero, C. (2010) The significance of subspecies: a case study of Sage Sparrows (Emberizidae, Amphispiza belli). Chapter 9 In Winker, K., and S. M. Haig, S. M. (Eds.), Avian Subspecies. Ornithological Monographs no. 67." type="book" year="2010">Cicero (2010:113)</bibRefCitation>
has also recently suggested deserves specific status. The species 
<taxonomicName id="1BFE14F5FFAD9E2EFF20FA45E0B3FA17" box="[151,198,1459,1482]" class="Aves" family="Emberizidae" genus="Emberiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="belli">
<emphasis id="EE8AB364FFAD9E2EFF20FA45E0B3FA17" box="[151,198,1459,1482]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="67">belli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
includes the subspecies 
<taxonomicName id="1BFE14F5FFAD9E2EFE7BFA45E2D6FA17" authority="(Townsend)" baseAuthorityName="Townsend" box="[460,675,1459,1482]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Artemisia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="cinerea">
<emphasis id="EE8AB364FFAD9E2EFE7BFA45E26EFA17" box="[460,539,1459,1482]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="67">cinerea</emphasis>
(Townsend)
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="1BFE14F5FFAD9E2EFD19FA45E3E7FA17" authority="(Ridgway)" baseAuthorityName="Ridgway" box="[686,914,1459,1482]" class="Aves" family="Emberizidae" genus="Pipilo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="clementae">
<emphasis id="EE8AB364FFAD9E2EFD19FA45E36FFA17" box="[686,794,1459,1482]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="67">clementae</emphasis>
(Ridgway)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="1BFE14F5FFAD9E2EFC71FA45E4D3FA17" authority="(Grinnell)" baseAuthorityName="Grinnell" box="[966,1190,1459,1482]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Artemisia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="canescens">
<emphasis id="EE8AB364FFAD9E2EFC71FA45E447FA17" box="[966,1074,1459,1482]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="67">canescens</emphasis>
(Grinnell)
</taxonomicName>
, fide 
<bibRefCitation id="B86F1287FFAD9E2EFB56FA45E50FFA17" author="Cicero, C." box="[1249,1402,1459,1482]" pageId="0" pageNumber="67" refId="ref622" refString="Cicero, C. (2010) The significance of subspecies: a case study of Sage Sparrows (Emberizidae, Amphispiza belli). Chapter 9 In Winker, K., and S. M. Haig, S. M. (Eds.), Avian Subspecies. Ornithological Monographs no. 67." type="book" year="2010">Cicero (2010)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
